{"response":"# Real-Time Block Retrieval for Frontend Developers

For a frontend developer to retrieve blocks in real-time and display live block production information, there are several approaches you can implement. Based on the Studio Blockchain Indexer we've been working with, here's how you can achieve this:

## Approach 1: Polling with Optimized Intervals

Since the indexer doesn't appear to have native WebSocket support, the most straightforward approach is to implement intelligent polling:

```javascript
// Example using React and axios
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

function BlockExplorer() {
  const [latestBlocks, setLatestBlocks] = useState([]);
  const [lastKnownBlock, setLastKnownBlock] = useState(0);
  const BASE_URL = 'https://mainnetindexer.studio-blockchain.com';

  // Function to fetch the latest blocks
  const fetchLatestBlocks = async () => {
    try {
      // First check the latest block number from the health endpoint
      const healthResponse = await axios.get(`${BASE_URL}/health`);
      const latestBlockNumber = healthResponse.data.lastBlock;

      // If we have new blocks, fetch them
      if (latestBlockNumber > lastKnownBlock) {
        const blocksResponse = await axios.get(`${BASE_URL}/blocks?limit=10`);
        setLatestBlocks(blocksResponse.data);
        setLastKnownBlock(latestBlockNumber);
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Error fetching blocks:', error);
    }
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    // Initial fetch
    fetchLatestBlocks();

    // Set up polling - adjust interval based on block production rate
    // For a new blockchain with sparse blocks, 5-10 seconds might be appropriate
    const interval = setInterval(fetchLatestBlocks, 5000);

    return () => clearInterval(interval);
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Latest Blocks</h1>
      <div className="blocks-container">
        {latestBlocks.map(block => (
          <div key={block.number} className="block-card">
            <h3>Block #{block.number}</h3>
            <p>Hash: {block.hash.substring(0, 10)}...</p>
            <p>Timestamp: {new Date(block.timestamp * 1000).toLocaleString()}</p>
            <p>Transactions: {block.transactions.length}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Approach 2: Adaptive Polling

Since block production might be irregular, you can implement adaptive polling that adjusts the polling frequency based on block production rate:

```javascript
function adaptivePolling() {
  let pollInterval = 5000; // Start with 5 seconds
